PEEP-II Ratings Data Dictionary

Rick O. Gilmore

2019-07-17 12:44:09

1 Background

A MATLAB script (https://github.com/gilmore-lab/peep-II/tree/master/peep-II-script) was used to play sounds and record participant responses.

2 Ratings files

The script saved a comma-delimited (.csv) text file for each participant’s testing session. The ratings file name contains relevant data elements, and so does the file itself.

2.1 Ratings file name format

rating- + <fam_id> + - + <YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM> + -run- + <run> + -order- + <order> + .csv.

The <YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM> is a timestamp of the start of data collection.

2.2 Fields within ratings file

2.2.1 fam_id

An integer [1,999] for the target family. The same identifier is used for the target child and for the target child’s mother.

2.2.2 nov_id

An integer [1,999] identifying the novel or control family.

2.2.3 run

A numeric code [1,2] indicating the order in which the two, 32-trial runs were presented. This should match the order presented to the participant during the fMRI data collection.

2.2.4 order

A numeric code [1,4] indicating which of four orders of scripts was presented to the participant.

2.2.5 sound_index

An integer [1,32] indexing the presentation order of the sound within a given 32-trial run.

2.2.6 snd_file

The local file name/path to the sound file presented for ratings during the indicated trial. The file name is structured as follows:

“wav/” + <fam_id> + “/norm/” + <fam_id> or <nov_id> + {‘ang’,‘hap’,‘neu’,sad’} + “/” + {‘chk’,‘din’,‘hlp’,‘tlk’} + “/” + {‘a’,‘b’} + “.wav”

The <fam_id> is the family identifier for this participant. The specific sound file presented could involve the mother of this participant with <fam_id> or the mother of the other, novel or control family with <nov_id>.

The target prosody for the sound file could be angry (‘ang’), happy (‘hap’), non-emotional (‘neu’ for neutral), or sad (‘sad’).

The script theme concerned the checkbook (‘chk’), dinner (‘din’), a request for help (‘hlp’), and a request to talk (‘tlk’).

There were two versions of the scripts within each theme, ‘a’ and ‘b’.

2.2.7 happy_rating

A numeric rating [1,4] in response to the question ‘How HAPPY does this sound?’. A rating of one showed the same neutral face as the sad_rating and angry_rating. Ratings 2 and greater indicated increasing intensity of perceived happiness.

1 2 3 4

2.2.8 angry_rating

A numeric rating [1,4] in response to the question ‘How ANGRY does this sound?’. A rating of one showed the same neutral face as the happy_rating and sad_rating. Ratings 2 and greater indicated increasing intensity of perceived anger.

1 2 3 4

2.2.9 sad_rating

A numeric rating [1,4] in response to the question: ‘How SAD does this sound?’. A rating of one showed the same neutral face as the happy_rating and angry_rating. Ratings 2 and greater indicated increasing intensity of perceived sadness.

1 2 3 4

2.2.10 how_feel

A rating [1,5] indicating the participant’s answer to the question: ‘How does this make you feel?’.

Images presented were the midscale (intensity = 3) of the happy, sad, and angry ratings used in the study. An additional scared scale was generated for this purpose, and the intensity = 3 image used here.

Neutral Happy Angry Sad Scared
1 2 3 4 5

2.2.11 know_speaker

An integer [1,2] made in response to the question ‘Do you know who is being spoken to?’.

Yes No
1 2

2.2.12 scared.rating

A numeric rating [1,4] in response to the question: ‘How SCARED does this sound?’. A rating of one showed the same neutral face as the happy_rating, angry_rating, and sad_rating. Ratings 2 and greater indicated increasing intensity of perceived sadness.

1 2 3 4
